Nairobi governor hopeful Peter Kenneth says the city is dirty, congested and in disarray, but he has a master plan to restore sanity to the capital.He also criticised Nairobi Senator Mike Sonko &mdash; a rival for the Jubilee Party ticket &mdash; for calling him an outsider and organising opposition to him.Kenneth was born and reared in Nairobi, though his family home is in Murang&rsquo;a.Speaking on Sunday at the Redeemed Gospel Church in Huruma. Kenneth said hostile actions have been carried out by a faction allied to Sonko. &ldquo;We have seen incidents where goons are used to cause chaos in the past few weeks. I caution those eyeing political seats to exercise tolerance. Elections are competitive and we all must be positive about them,&rdquo; the former Gatanga MP said. He said he has a right to run and will not bow to pressure to quit. Kenneth said, however, he will work with whoever wins the ticket. &ldquo;As you can see, the state of roads, environment and many other aspects making the city habitable, are in disarray. We want to decongest Nairobi, clean it and restore sanity,&rdquo; he said. Others seeking the JP ticket are Dagoretti South MP Dennis Waweru, former Starehe MP Margaret Wanjiru and nominated MP Johnson Sakaja.